# Prototype top tabs — independent surfaces

The Home prototype has **Admin**, **Channel Manager**, and **Partner View** (`page.tsx`: `activeTopView`). Slack shell content uses `topViewMode` on `SlackAppShell`, `AppHeader`, `DemoSidebar`, `DemoIconBar`, and related views.

## Rule

- **Channel Manager** requests apply **only** when `topViewMode === "channel-manager"` (or the equivalent branch). Do **not** change Partner styling, copy, data, or behavior unless the user asks for Partner too.
- **Partner View** requests apply **only** when `topViewMode === "seller"` (`partner-shell` / `partner-chrome`). Do **not** change Channel Manager unless explicitly requested.
- **Admin** is the iframe path — separate from both Slack modes.

## Implementation pattern

- Prefer **explicit branches**: `topViewMode === "channel-manager" ? … : …`, `topViewMode === "seller" ? … : …`, or `cn(..., isPartnerView && …)`.
- Avoid **shared defaults** that silently affect both tabs; if a default exists, document which tab it belongs to or split props per mode.
- **Global CSS** (e.g. `.slack-app-header`) must not force one tab’s look onto the other — use wrapper classes/data attributes per mode if global rules are needed.

## When the user specifies a tab

If they say “in Channel Manager” or “on the Partner tab,” treat that as **hard scope**: gate the diff to that mode only and leave the other tab unchanged.
